column3: expected_definition
column8: predicted_definition

column3: Concentration of S-sulfocysteine in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.
column8: An abnormally increased level of S-sulfocysteine in the blood circulation.

column3: Concentration of DOPA (3,4-dihydroxyphenylalanine) in the blood circulation above the upper limit of normal.
column8: An elevated plasma concentration of dihydroxyphenylalanine (DOPA).

column3: A developmental anomnaly characterized by the lack of development of the posterior communicating artery.
column8: A developmental anomnaly characterized by underdevelopment of the posterior communicating artery.

column3: The concentration of guanidinoacetic acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is below the lower limit of normal.
column8: An elevated urine level of a compound that is derived from guanidinoacetic acid.
Reduction in the level of epidermal proteins

column3: An unpleasant sensation characterized by physical discomfort (such as pricking, throbbing, or aching) localized to the eyelid.
column8: Pain localized to the eyelid.

column3: The presence of a nodule (small rounded lump of tissue) in the iris.
Accumulation of antigen-bound antibody in the skin.
column8: The presence of dermal immune complex deposits in the skin.

column3: Enzyme activity of aromatase below the lower limit of normal.
column8: Decreased activity of the enzyme aromatase, which is responsible for converting androgens to estrogen in women and men.

column3: Applied to a sign or symptom that is worsened by administration of phenytoin.
column8: Applied to a sign or symptom that is worsened by ingestion of phenytoin.

column2: Altered location of the longitudinal column in the fibrous sheath
column3: The fibrous sheath is a structure in the midpiece of the sperm flagellum surrounding the outer dense fibers. It comprises two longitudinal columns and tranverse ribs. In case of altered location of the longitudinal column in the fibrous sheath the symmetrical structure is lost, most commonly with the columns not being opposite to each other, which can be visualised by electron microscopy.
column8: A structural abnormality where the sperm tail is not located correctly within the fibrous sheath.

column2: Entamoeba histolytica antibody positive in stool
column3: Demonstration of antibody directed against Entamoeba histolytica in stool.
column8: Identification of Entamoeba histolytica, a protozoan parasite that causes amoebic dysentery, in the stool.

column3: Applies to a sign or symptom that is improved or made more bearable by treatment with thiamine.
column8: Applies to a sign or symptom that is improved or made more bearable by treatment with thiamine.

column3: Amount of keratin 14 in the epidermis below the lower limit of normal. The findiong is typically ascertained by immunofluorescent microscopy.
column8: A condition characterized by decreased levels of the epidermal keratin 14 protein.

column3: A history of following a vegan diet characterized by avoidance of food sourced from animals including meet, fish, and dairy products.
column8: A plant-based diet that excludes all animal products, including meat, dairy, eggs and honey.

column3: Any structural anomaly of the keratinocyte. The keratinocyte is the major cell type of the epidermis and is responsible for generating the protective barrier.
column8: An abnormality in the shape or structure of keratinocytes, which are cells that make up the outermost layer of skin.

column3: Sharply angled insertion of the neck and midpiece into the head of a spermatozoon. This term applies if the proportion of spermatozoa with this feature is above the upper limit of normal.
column8: A structural abnormality in which the sperm neck is bent or curved.

column3: Information about current or past medications taken by an individual.
column8: Medications taken by the patient during pregnancy

column3: Concentration of glutathione in red blood cells below the lower limit of normal. Glutathione (GSH) is an important redox active biomolecule critical in the maintenance and regulation of cellular and organismal health.
column8: This term refers to an inappropriate low level of glutathione, a potent antioxidant and detoxicant present in erythrocytes. Reduced concentration may result from increased oxidative stress or impaired synthesis.

column3: The presence of inclusion bodies within the cytoplasm of muscle cells that contain a mxiture of granules and filaments.
column8: Intracytoplasmic inclusions in myofibers composed of granules and filaments, possibly derived from membranous structures.

column3: A history of exposure during pregnancy of the mother of a fetus or child to cytarabine.
column8: A history of fetal exposure to cytarabine.

column3: Lymph node with increased numbers of macrophages heavily laden with lipids.
column8: The presence of lipid droplets within lymphatic system macrophages, which are typically found in adipose tissue.

column3: History of having taken a calcium channel blocker such as amlodipine, nicardipine, nifedipine, verapamil, or diltiazem.
column8: Present in the medical record as a medication taken by the patient, typically within the last year.

column2: Asymmetrical insertion of the midpiece into the head
column3: Insertion of the neck and midpiece into the head of a spermatozoon on an axis that diverges from the midline axis of the spermatozoon head. This term applies if the proportion of spermatozoa with this defect is above the upper limit of normal.
column8: An abnormality in which one end of the sperm midpiece is inserted more deeply into the head than the other.

column3: A break or tear in the trachea.
column8: Breakage (tear) of the trachea.

column3: The mother of a fetus or index patient has a history of hyperthyroidism during the corresponding pregnancy.
column8: Maternal hyperthyroidism is a condition in which the thyroid gland produces excessive amounts of thyroid hormones. This can lead to an increased risk of certain complications during pregnancy, such as premature labor or low birth weight.

column2: Reduced epidermal bullous pemphigoid antigen 1 protein expression
column3: Lower than normal amount of bullous pemphigoid antigen 1 (BP230) in the epidermis.
Eruption of permanent teeth behind deciduous (baby) teeth before they have fallen out, resulting in a double row of teeth. This phenomen is typically observed between the ages of 5 to 7 years.
column8:
A developmental anomaly characterized by the delayed or absent eruption
of certain teeth, usually the deciduous dentition. It is often associated with other
developmental abnormalities.

column3: Deposition of a largely amorphous hyaline (transparent and homogeneous) substance around blood vessels in the wall of the small intestine.

Diminished activity of the enzyme enolase in muscle tissue. The enzyme enolase catalyzes the interconversion of 2-phosphoglycerate and phosphoenolpyruvate. In adult human muscle, over 90% of enolase activity is accounted for by the beta-enolase subunit, the protein product of the ENO3 gene.
column8: A decrease in the level or activity of the enzyme enolase, usually measured in a muscle biopsy specimen.

column3: Concentration of apolipoprotein E above the upper limit of normal.
column8: An increase in the blood concentration of apolipoprotein E.

column3: Occuring on the left and right in succession. This term can refer to alternating sides of the body (e.g., Alternating hemiplegia) or alternative sides of the visual field (e.g., some migraine auras).
column8: Alternation between right and left sided phenotypic abnormalities.

column3: The concentration of norepinephrine in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is below the lower limit of normal.
column8: A reduced concentration of norepinephrine in urine.

column3: Concentration of norepinephrin in the blood circulation below the lower limit of normal.
column8: An decreased level of norepinephrine in the blood.

column3: A structural abnormality of the knee joint or surrounding structures.
column8: Abnormality of the form, structure or size of the knee joint.

column3:
Abnormal structure of the rete ridges (also known as rete pegs), which are
downward projections of epithelium surrounding the connective tissue papillae in between the dermal papillae.
column8: An abnormality in the structure of the rete ridges.

column3: Concentration or activity of an arylsulfatase C as measured in leukocytes is below the limits of normal in the blood circulation.
column8: An abnormally decreased amount of leukocyte steroid sulfatase activity.

column3: Width of the cavum septum pellucidum above the upper limit of normal, which is defined as a separation of greater than one cm of the leaves of the cavum septum pellucidum.
column8: An abnormally wide cavity in the septum pellucidum, which is a thin, triangular, vertical membrane separating the lateral ventricles of the brain.

column2: Abnormal leukocyte enzyme concentration or activity
column3: Concentration or activity of an enzyme as measured in leukocytes is above or below the limits of normal in the blood circulation.
column8: An increased or decreased level of an enzyme in the blood that is specific to leukocytes.

column3: Downward pointing exostoses of the occipital bone situated in the tendinous insertions of the sternocleidomastoid and trapezius muscles.
column8: A bony projection or outgrowth on the posterior aspect of the skull, typically associated with abnormalities in the occipital bone.

column3: Accumulation of monoclonal CD1a-positive Langerhans cells in the bronchioles and alveolar interstitium that can cause damage to the lungs.
column8: A condition characterized by the accumulation of Langerhans cells in the lungs.

column3: The concentration of formiminoglutamic acid in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is above the upper limit of normal.
column8: An increased amount of formiminoglutamic acid in the urine.

column3: Concentration of antidiuretic hormone, also known as vasopressin, is below the lower limit of normal in the blood circulation.
column8: A state of decreased circulating levels of Antidiuretic hormone, despite hyponatremia and hypo-osmolality with normal or increased plasma volume.

column3: A gastrinoma, a neuroendocrine tumors characterized by the secretion of gastrin with resultant excessive gastric acid production, that is localized to the duodenum.
column8: A benign or malignant tumor that secretes excessive amounts of the hormone gastrin, which can lead to hyperacidity and peptic ulceration.

column3: The concentration of epinephrine in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is below the lower limit of normal.
column8: The concentration of epinephrine in the urine, normalized for urine concentration, is below the lower limit of normal.

column3: Amount of erythritol in the urine above the upper limit of normal.
column8: An abnormally increased concentration of erythritol in the urine.

column3: Excessive proliferation of fibroblasts and deposition of extracellular matrix within the ovary.
column8: A condition characterized by the presence of fibrous tissue in or around the ovary.

column3: A highly aggressive, extremely rare neoplasm of the ovary that is usually seen in children. The term rhabdoid is used because the tumor cells resemble rhabdomyoblasts but lack myogenic markers.
column8: A highly aggressive, extremely rare neoplasm of the ovary that is usually seen in children. The term rhabdoid is used because the tumor cells resemble rhabdomyoblasts but lack myogenic markers, and pathologic diagnosis requires familiarity with these microscopic features plus awareness that adult onset is possible.

column3: Lack of observable peroxisomes. This feature can be observed by immunohistochemical staining of cultured cells (such as fibroblasts) or by electronmicroscopy.
column8: The absence or complete loss of function in peroxisomes.
An abnormality of an extrahepatic bile duct.
